Thanks, that's great!
Thanks! Here are a few remarks.
Only style stuff.
Thanks, that's great!
Comments on the first two files (will post comments on the other two once my laptop compiles the files in between)

```suggestion
lemma intervalIntegrable_iff_ofReal {μ : Measure ℝ} {a b : ℝ} {f : ℝ → ℝ} (hab: a ≤ b) :
    IntervalIntegrable f μ a b ↔ IntervalIntegrable (fun x ↦ (f x : ℂ)) μ a b := by
  repeat rw [intervalIntegrable_iff_integrableOn_Ioc_of_le]
  apply integrableOn_iff_ofReal
  all_goals exact hab
```

I think you should rather put this lemma in `MeasureTheory.Integral.IntervalIntegral`, as there is a section about `IntervalIntegrable` in it. Once you moved it, check which objects are already defined to avoid adding unnecessary hypotheses. You can use `#where` in a a file to check which variables are defined.
Moved and renamed as well to iff_ofReal in namespace IntervalIntegrable

Instead of adding just this lemma, could you please copy-paste the `RCLike` section of `MeasureTheory.Function.L1Space` to the bottom of the file and rewrite everything with `IntegrableOn`? All the proofs should just be the corresponding statement for `Integrable`.

I've added all of these lemma's, but I'm struggling through proving
```
theorem IntegrableOn.re_im_iff {f : X → ℂ} :
    IntegrableOn (fun x => (f x).re) s μ ∧ IntegrableOn (fun x => (f x).im) s μ ↔
      IntegrableOn f s μ
```
`Integrable.re_im_iff (f := f)` works
Fixed!

Can you please put it in an `RCLike` section just after `IntegrableOn.setLIntegral_lt_top` (line 340)? That way you need not introduce `X`, `μ` and `s`, nor to reopen namespace, and it makes more sense with the content of the file.

It's better to reuse types which are already introduced in a file for consistency. Can you put this below `Integrable.im`?
```suggestion
lemma Integrable.iff_ofReal {f : α → ℝ} : Integrable f μ ↔ Integrable (fun x ↦ (f x : ℂ)) μ :=
  ⟨fun hf ↦ hf.ofReal, fun hf ↦ hf.re⟩
```
fixed

Better naming + already declared variable:
```suggestion
theorem Complex.integral_re {f : X → ℂ} (hf : Integrable f μ) :
    ∫ x, (f x).re ∂μ = (∫x, f x ∂μ).re := _root_.integral_re hf

theorem setIntegral_re {s : Set X} {f : X → ℂ} (hf : IntegrableOn f s μ) :
    ∫ x in s, (f x).re ∂μ = (∫x in s, f x ∂μ).re := Complex.integral_re hf.integrable
```
fixed

I'm sorry it wasn't clear, when I said "copy the RCLike section of `L1Space`", I literally meant it, in particular writing those with a function taking values in an RCLike field rather than complex numbers.
Ohh I see. Okay, will fix this
fixed

```suggestion
  ⟨fun hf ↦ hf.ofReal, fun hf ↦ hf.re⟩
```

The proof needs only one indent, see [here](https://leanprover-community.github.io/contribute/style.html#structuring-definitions-and-theorems).
```suggestion
  repeat rw [intervalIntegral.integral_of_le hab]
  apply setIntegral_re
  rw [← intervalIntegrable_iff_integrableOn_Ioc_of_le hab]
  exact hf
```

```suggestion
  MeasureTheory.Integrable.iff_ofReal
```

```suggestion
    IntegrableOn (fun x => RCLike.re (f x)) s μ := (IntegrableOn.re_im_iff.2 hf).left
```
This is in `section RCLike` but doesn't actually use the RCLike typeclass. Did you perhaps want `fun x ↦ (f x : 𝕜)` in the RHS? This will work if you make the change I suggested in the L1Space file.

Maybe you want to allow a function valued in the  `RCLike` field `𝕜` here? You can do this with
```suggestion
lemma Integrable.iff_ofReal {f : α → ℝ} : Integrable f μ ↔ Integrable (fun x ↦ (f x : 𝕜)) μ :=
  ⟨fun hf ↦ hf.ofReal, fun hf ↦ by simpa only [RCLike.ofReal_re] using hf.re⟩
```

```suggestion
theorem IntegrableOn.ofReal {f : α → ℝ} (hf : IntegrableOn f s μ) :
    IntegrableOn (fun x ↦ (f x : 𝕜)) s μ :=
  Integrable.ofReal hf
```

please put proof on a new line:
```suggestion
theorem IntegrableOn.re_im_iff {f : α → 𝕜} :
    IntegrableOn (fun x => RCLike.re (f x)) s μ ∧ IntegrableOn (fun x => RCLike.im (f x)) s μ ↔
    IntegrableOn f s μ := 
  Integrable.re_im_iff
```
(& likewise in a couple of other lemmas).

This works, but I would suggest maybe going for
```suggestion
theorem IntegrableOn.re {f : α → 𝕜} (hf : IntegrableOn f s μ) :
    IntegrableOn (fun x => RCLike.re (f x)) s μ :=
  Integrable.re hf
```
since this makes clear that it is essentially an IntegrableOn restatement of an existing Integrable lemma. (Ditto for the next lemma.)

Can you say what this is needed for? I am wondering why it isn't covered by `integral_re` above, since `ℂ` is of course an example of an `RCLike` field. If it is needed, then we should presumably have the `im` version too (and likewise for the next lemma). Note also spacing `∫ x` not `∫x`.

(Incidentally, I admit that I'm a bit puzzled why the root-level lemma `integral_re` is placed in this file `SetIntegral`, since it doesn't actually involve set integrals! But that is a question for another PR.)

The proof can be golfed to a one-liner
`simpa only [intervalIntegrable_iff_integrableOn_Ioc_of_le hab] using IntegrableOn.iff_ofReal`. I guess the statement generalises to `RCLike` as well. 

Is the `hab` hypothesis needed? I think it probably shouldn't be, because `IntervalIntegrable` is symmetric; and this gives us less conditions to check when the lemma is applied.

In statement `hf:` -> `hf :`. Again, I suspect the statement is true without `hab`, and for an `RCLike` field rather than just `ℂ`. The proof can be shortened to
```
  simpa only [integral_of_le hab] using 
    setIntegral_re <| (intervalIntegrable_iff_integrableOn_Ioc_of_le hab).mp hf
```
(note that you don't need the fully qualified name `intervalIntegral.integral_of_le`, just `integral_of_le` is enough, because you're already inside the `intervalIntegral` namespace).

Do we want a version of this lemma for `im` as well?
